<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  OWASP Dependency-Check suppression file.

  Wired into the `org.owasp.dependencycheck` plugin in the root build.gradle.kts
  via `dependencyCheck { suppressionFile = ... }`. Every entry below MUST carry
  a `notes` block that explains *why* the finding is suppressed so the next
  weekly Monday scan does not require re-deriving the justification from
  scratch.

  Categories accepted:
    1. CPE confusion - the NVD entry refers to a different product that shares
       a token (e.g. "line", "spring boot tools") with the dependency we ship.
    2. Build-time-only path - the affected JAR is on the buildscript /
       checkstyle / pitest plugin classpath, never reaches the
       runtime classpath of the deployed Spring Boot fat JAR.
    3. Nested JAR inside a build-time tool - same as #2 but the SHA-1 match
       happens because OWASP unpacks a fat tool JAR and inspects the
       embedded JARs.

  Real production CVEs are NEVER suppressed; they are fixed by upgrading the
  dependency to a patched version (see build.gradle.kts dependency overrides).
-->
<suppressions xmlns="https://jeremylong.github.io/DependencyCheck/dependency-suppression.1.3.xsd">

  <!--
    pitest-command-line carries the artifact id "pitest" but the OWASP CPE
    matcher attributes CVE-2015-0897 (a MITM bug in the "LINE" Android/iOS
    messenger app) to it because the messenger's vendor/product CPE happens
    to be "cpe:2.3:a:line:line". The library has no relation to LINE Corp;
    it is a JVM mutation testing tool. CVSS for this CVE is 5.9 (under our
    7.0 fail-build gate) but the SARIF report would still surface the
    finding noisily to GitHub Security every week.
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes>False positive: CPE confusion. CVE-2015-0897 targets the "LINE" Android/iOS messenger app (cpe:2.3:a:line:line) and has nothing to do with the pitest mutation testing library.</notes>
    <packageUrl regex="true">^pkg:maven/org\.pitest/pitest-command-line@.*$</packageUrl>
    <cve>CVE-2015-0897</cve>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    spring-boot-devtools (Spring Boot 4.x) is wrongly matched against the
    `cpe:2.3:a:vmware:spring_boot_tools` / `cpe:2.3:a:vmware:spring_tools`
    CPEs. CVE-2022-31691 is a deserialization gadget in **Spring Tools 4
    for Eclipse** plus the VSCode "Spring Boot Tools", "Concourse CI Pipeline
    Editor", "Bosh Editor" and "Cloudfoundry Manifest YML Support" extensions
    - none of which we ship. The Spring Boot runtime devtools module is a
    distinct artifact and is gated to the `development` profile only.
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes>False positive: CPE confusion. CVE-2022-31691 affects Spring Tools 4 for Eclipse and a set of VSCode plugins; it does not apply to the Spring Boot runtime devtools dependency.</notes>
    <packageUrl regex="true">^pkg:maven/org\.springframework\.boot/spring-boot-devtools@.*$</packageUrl>
    <cve>CVE-2022-31691</cve>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    The io.opentelemetry.semconv jars (opentelemetry-semconv /
    opentelemetry-semconv-incubating, pulled by the Boot 4 OpenTelemetry
    starter and by the Keycloak server SPI compile classpath) contain only
    generated semantic-convention CONSTANTS - no network, parsing or
    process-spawning code. The NVD matcher maps them onto the umbrella CPE
    `cpe:2.3:a:opentelemetry:opentelemetry`, which aggregates the whole
    OpenTelemetry product family across languages; every CVE filed against
    the *Go* SDK whose version range happens to contain 1.37/1.41 then
    lights up these Java jars. Concretely flagged in week 2026-W27:
    CVE-2026-29181 (Go baggage-header DoS, fixed in otel-go 1.41.0),
    CVE-2026-24051 and CVE-2026-39883 (Go macOS/BSD PATH-hijack in
    host-resource detection, fixed in otel-go 1.40.0/1.43.0). Suppressing
    the CPE mapping itself (not individual CVEs) is the documented
    dependency-check remedy for CPE confusion and keeps every future
    Go/Collector CVE from re-triggering this false positive. Real CVEs
    against the io.opentelemetry *Java* artifacts use distinct CPEs and
    remain visible.
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes>False positive: CPE confusion. The opentelemetry-semconv Java jars are constants-only; the umbrella cpe:/a:opentelemetry:opentelemetry attributes OpenTelemetry-Go SDK CVEs (CVE-2026-29181, CVE-2026-24051, CVE-2026-39883) to them by pure version-number overlap.</notes>
    <packageUrl regex="true">^pkg:maven/io\.opentelemetry\.semconv/opentelemetry-semconv.*@.*$</packageUrl>
    <cpe>cpe:/a:opentelemetry:opentelemetry</cpe>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    Belt-and-braces companion to the CPE suppression above: the same five
    OpenTelemetry-GO SDK CVEs pinned by id, in case a future
    dependency-check version changes how partial-CPE matching works. All
    five are Go-SDK-only (baggage-header DoS and macOS/BSD PATH-hijack in
    host-resource detection - see the notes above); none has any Java
    counterpart. CVE-2026-39882 and CVE-2026-41178 sit below the 7.0 gate
    but would still spam the weekly SARIF upload.
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes>False positive: CPE confusion (companion to the CPE-level entry). CVE-2026-29181, CVE-2026-24051, CVE-2026-39883, CVE-2026-39882 and CVE-2026-41178 are OpenTelemetry-Go SDK vulnerabilities attributed to the constants-only Java semconv jars.</notes>
    <packageUrl regex="true">^pkg:maven/io\.opentelemetry\.semconv/opentelemetry-semconv.*@.*$</packageUrl>
    <cve>CVE-2026-29181</cve>
    <cve>CVE-2026-24051</cve>
    <cve>CVE-2026-39883</cve>
    <cve>CVE-2026-39882</cve>
    <cve>CVE-2026-41178</cve>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    CVE-2026-53914 is an unsafe-deserialization bug in the Kotlin BUILD
    TOOLCHAIN (< 2.4.20): malicious build-cache metadata can execute code
    during compilation. JetBrains' own CNA vector is local/high-privilege
    (CVSS 6.7); the NVD auto-score of 9.8 CRITICAL is what trips our gate.
    The artifact we actually ship is the RUNTIME kotlin-stdlib jar
    (transitive via okhttp/okio, the OTLP exporter's HTTP sender) which
    contains no build-cache handling code, and basetool compiles zero
    Kotlin sources - the vulnerable toolchain path cannot be reached.
    CVE-scoped (not CPE-scoped) on purpose: a future CVE against the
    stdlib itself must still fail the build.
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes>False positive: CVE-2026-53914 targets the Kotlin build toolchain's build-cache metadata deserialization, not the runtime kotlin-stdlib jar we ship transitively via okhttp/okio; this project compiles no Kotlin sources.</notes>
    <packageUrl regex="true">^pkg:maven/org\.jetbrains\.kotlin/kotlin-stdlib@.*$</packageUrl>
    <cve>CVE-2026-53914</cve>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    CVE-2026-42582 is an allocation-DoS in the QPACK decoder of
    netty-codec-http3 4.2.0.Alpha1 - 4.2.12 (fixed 4.2.13.Final). The
    netty 4.1.x line does not contain the HTTP/3 codec at all - it lives
    in the 4.2+ line - so ANY 4.1.x jar is outside the affected range;
    the broad cpe:2.3:a:netty:netty match flags them anyway. Our 4.1.135
    jars additionally sit only on the keycloak-spi compile classpath
    (Keycloak server internals, container-provided at runtime); the app
    modules resolve netty 4.2.15.Final, which is above the fixed version.
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes>False positive: CPE confusion. CVE-2026-42582 affects netty-codec-http3 in the 4.2.0-4.2.12 range; the netty 4.1.x line ships no HTTP/3 codec, and these jars are Keycloak-container-provided compile-time deps anyway.</notes>
    <packageUrl regex="true">^pkg:maven/io\.netty/netty\-.*@4\.1\..*$</packageUrl>
    <cve>CVE-2026-42582</cve>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    CVE-2024-7254 (unbounded recursion -> StackOverflowError when parsing
    untrusted nested groups, fixed in protobuf-java 3.25.5) is a REAL
    protobuf-java CVE - but protobuf-java 3.25.1 exists exclusively on the
    keycloak-spi module's compileOnly classpath, dragged in by the Keycloak
    server artifacts (Infinispan/protostream) the SPI compiles against.
    Verified via `dependencyInsight`: no basetool runtime classpath
    (backend/frontend/ingest/keycloak-spi runtime) contains protobuf-java
    in any version. At runtime the SPI runs inside the Keycloak container,
    which supplies its own (Red Hat-patched) protobuf; upgrading the pin in
    our build would change nothing that ships. Version-pinned to 3.25.1 so
    a vulnerable protobuf appearing on a REAL classpath later still fails
    the build.
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes>Build-time-only: protobuf-java 3.25.1 is a compileOnly transitive of the Keycloak server artifacts the keycloak-spi module compiles against; it is container-provided at runtime and absent from every basetool runtime classpath, so the CVE-2024-7254 parsing path never ships.</notes>
    <packageUrl regex="true">^pkg:maven/com\.google\.protobuf/protobuf-java@3\.25\.1$</packageUrl>
    <cve>CVE-2024-7254</cve>
  </suppress>

  <!--
    plexus-utils 3.3.0 is pulled in transitively by Checkstyle 13.4.2 via
    `org.apache.maven.doxia:doxia-core`/`doxia-module-xdoc` (Checkstyle's
    Javadoc/site-rendering helper), which is exclusively on the
    `checkstyleMain` configuration. It is never on the runtime classpath of
    the deployed application. CVE-2025-67030 is a `Expand.extractFile` zip
    slip - we do not call that method anywhere, and Checkstyle itself only
    invokes it during local report rendering, not when scanning sources.
  -->
  <suppress>
    <notes>Build-time-only: plexus-utils 3.3.0 is a transitive dependency of Checkstyle (doxia-core). The Expand.extractFile zip slip is unreachable through Checkstyle's source-scanning path and the JAR never ships in the deployed Spring Boot fat JAR.</notes>
    <packageUrl regex="true">^pkg:maven/org\.codehaus\.plexus/plexus-utils@3\.3\.0$</packageUrl>
    <cve>CVE-2025-67030</cve>
  </suppress>

</suppressions>
